# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: safety-integrity-level
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] There are four ASILs identified by the standard: ASIL A, ASIL B, ASIL C, ASIL D.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ASIL D dictates the highest integrity requirements on the product and ASIL A the lowest.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Hazards that are identified as QM do not dictate any safety requirements.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Because of the reference to SIL and because the ASIL incorporate 4 levels of hazard with a 5th non-hazardous level, it is common in descriptions of ASIL to compare its levels to the SIL levels and DO-178C Design Assurance Levels, respectively.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The determination of ASIL is the result of *hazard analysis and risk assessment*.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] In the context of ISO 26262, a hazard is assessed based on the relative impact of hazardous effects related to a system, as adjusted for relative likelihoods of the hazard manifesting those effects.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] In short, ASIL refers both to risk and to risk-dependent requirements (standard minimal risk treatment for a given risk).
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] illustrating the role of Exposure and Controllability in establishing relative probability, which is combined with Severity to form an expression of risk.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The intervening levels are simply a range of intermediate degrees of hazard and degrees of assurance required.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ISO 26262 "highly recommends" the use of semi-formal modeling languages for ASIL D designs (Stateflow and SysML provide examples of such languages).
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Executable validation using either prototyping or simulation is mandatory.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Loss of braking for only the rear wheels is less dangerous, so this hazard is associated with ASIL C.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Another example of a less critical function that warrants the ASIL C rating is cruise control.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The use of semi-formal modeling languages is highly recommended for ASIL C designs.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ASIL B examples are headlights and brake lights.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Modeling of the ASIL B design can rely on an informal languages.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] This and other differences requirements make the cost difference between C and B to be the largest step across all the ASILs.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ASIL A is the lowest rating of the functional safety.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] A typical example are tail lights (non-braking).
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Less strict design walkthroughs can be used during the development (higher levels require more formal design inspections).
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Referring to "Quality Management", the QM level means that all assessed risks are tolerable from a safety perspective (even if the manufacturer might want to address them from a customer satisfaction perspective, for example make sure the vehicle starts).
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] So, safety assurance controls are unnecessary and standard quality management processes are sufficient for development.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Designing an entire system to the rigorous standards of the higher levels of ASIL can be unwieldy, so ISO 26262 allows "decomposition": redundant subcomponents, each designed to a lower ASIL level, can be combined into a higher ASIL level design using higher-level methodologies.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The subcomponents used in this way shall contain features that would allow higher-level integration.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The frequently used notation for an ASIL X-level component that can be used as a part of an ASIL Y-level system is X(Y).
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] For example, an A(B) component is designed at the ASIL A level of requirements, but is made to fit into ASIL B designs (this subcomponent is colloquially described as "B-ready").
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ISO 26262 contains multiple examples of allowed decomposition scenarios, for example ASIL B = A(B) + A(B), i.e. two redundant B-ready ASIL A subcomponents can be combined into an ASIL B design.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Headlights provide a natural example of such decomposition: there are at least two of them, so they can be designed at ASIL A and combined into an ASIL B system as long as the combination is done properly (for example, it should not introduce a common point of failure).
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Given ASIL is a relatively recent development, discussions of ASIL often compare its levels to levels defined in other well-established safety or quality management systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] In particular, the ASIL are compared to the SIL risk reduction levels defined in IEC 61508 and the Design Assurance Levels used in the context of DO-178C and DO-254.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] While there are some similarities, it is important to also understand the differences.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] IEC 61508 defines a widely referenced Safety Integrity Level (SIL) classification.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Unlike other functional safety standards, ISO 26262 does not provide normative nor informative mapping of ASIL to SIL; while the two standards have similar processes for hazard assessment, ASIL and SIL are computed from different perspectives.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] That is, for a given Tolerable Risk, greater Risk requires more risk reduction, i.e., a smaller design target value for greater probability of dangerous failure.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] For a safety function operating in high demand or continuous mode of operation, SIL 1 is associated with a probability of dangerous failure limit of 10−5 per hour while SIL 4 is associated with a probability of dangerous failure rate limit of 10−9 per hour.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] In commercial publications, ASIL D has been illustrated to align with SIL 3 and ASIL A is compared to SIL 1.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] While it is more common to compare the ISO 26262 Levels D through QM to the Design Assurance Levels (DAL) A through E and ascribe those levels to DO-178C; these DAL are actually defined and applied through the definitions of SAE ARP4761 and SAE ARP4754.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Especially in terms of the management of vehicular hazards through a Safety Life Cycle, the scope of ISO 26262 is more comparable to the combined scope of SAE ARP4761 and SAE ARP4754.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Functional Hazard Assessment (FHA) is defined in ARP4761 and the DAL are defined in ARP4754.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] DO-178C and DO-254 define the design assurance objectives that must be accomplished for given DAL.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Unlike SIL, it is the case that both ASIL and DAL are statements measuring degree of hazard.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] DAL E is the ARP4754 equivalent of QM; in both classifications hazards are negligible and safety management is not required.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] At the other end, DAL A and ASIL D represent the highest levels of risk addressed by the respective standards, but they do not address the same level of hazard.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] While ASIL D encompasses at most the hazards of a loaded passenger van, DAL A includes the greater hazards of large aircraft loaded with fuel and passengers.
[src:safety-integrity-level/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Publications might illustrate ASIL D as equivalent to either DAL B, to DAL A, or as an intermediate level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] A safety system (often called a safety-related system) consists of one or more safety functions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Functional safety is intrinsically end-to-end in scope in that it has to treat the function of a component or subsystem as part of the function of the entire automatic protection function of any system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Thus, although functional safety standards focus on electrical, electronic, and programmable systems (E/E/PS), the end-to-end scope means that in practice, functional safety methods must extend to the non-E/E/PS parts of the system that the E/E/PS actuators, valves, motor controls or monitors.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Functional safety is achieved when every specified safety function is carried out and the level of performance required of each safety function is met.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Assessment of the risk-reduction required by the safety function, which will involve a safety integrity level (SIL) or performance level or other quantification assessment.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] A SIL (or PL, AgPL, ASIL) applies to an end-to-end safety function of the safety-related system, not just to a component or a part of the system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Ensuring the safety function performs to the design intent, including under conditions of incorrect operator input and failure modes.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] This will involve having the design and lifecycle managed by qualified and competent engineers carrying out processes to a recognized functional safety standard.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] In Europe, that standard is IEC EN 61508, or one of the industry specific standards derived from IEC EN 61508, or for simple systems some other standard like ISO 13849.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Verification that the system meets the assigned SIL, ASIL, PL or agPL by determining the probability of dangerous failure, checking minimum levels of redundancy, and reviewing systematic capability (SC).
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] These three metrics have been called "the three barriers".
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Failure modes of a device are typically determined by failure mode and effects analysis of the system (FMEA).
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Failure probabilities for each failure mode are typically determined using failure mode, effects, and diagnostic analysis FMEDA.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Conduct functional safety audits to examine and assess the evidence that the appropriate safety lifecycle management techniques were applied consistently and thoroughly in the relevant lifecycle stages of product.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Neither safety nor functional safety can be determined without considering the system as a whole and the environment with which it interacts.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Functional safety is inherently end-to-end in scope.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Modern systems often have software intensively commanding and controlling safety-critical functions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Therefore, software functionality and correct software behavior must be part of the Functional safety engineering effort to ensure acceptable safety risk at the system level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Any claim of functional safety for a component, subsystem or system should be independently certified to one of the recognized functional safety standards.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] A certified product can then be claimed to be functionally safe to a particular safety integrity level or a performance level in a specific range of applications: the certificate and the assessment report is provided to the customers describing the scope and limits of performance.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Functional safety is a technically challenging field.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Certifications should be done by independent organizations with experience and strong technical depth (electronics, programmable electronics, mechanical, and probabilistic analysis).
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Functional safety certification is performed by accredited certification bodies (CB).
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Accreditation is awarded to a CB organization by an accreditation body (AB).
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] In the United States, the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) is the AB for functional safety accreditation.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] In the United Kingdom, the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) provides functional safety accreditation.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] ABs are members of the International Accreditation Forum (IAF) for work in management systems, products, services, and personnel accreditation or the International Laboratory Accreditation Cooperation (ILAC) for laboratory testing accreditation.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] A multilateral recognition arrangement (MLA) between ABs will ensure global recognition of accredited CBs.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] IEC 61508 functional safety certification programs have been established by several global Certification Bodies.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Each has defined their own scheme based upon IEC 61508 and other functional safety standards.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The scheme lists the referenced standards and specifies procedures which describes their test methods, surveillance audit policy, public documentation policies, and other specific aspects of their program.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Functional safety certification programs for IEC 61508 standards are being offered globally by several recognized CBs including Intertek, SGS, TÜV Rheinland, TÜV SÜD and UL.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] An important element of functional safety certification is on-going surveillance by the certification agency.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Most CB organizations have included surveillance audits in their scheme.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The follow-up surveillance ensures that the product, sub-system, or system is still being manufactured in accordance with what was originally certified for functional safety.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Follow-up surveillance may occur at various frequencies depending on the certification body, but will typically look at the product's field failure history, hardware design changes, software changes, as well as the manufacturer's ongoing compliance of functional safety management systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] For military aerospace and defense systems MIL-STD-882E addresses functional hazard analyses (FHA) and determining which functions implemented in hardware and software are safety significant.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The Functional safety focus is on ensuring safety critical functions and functional threads in the system, subsystem and software are analyzed and verified for correct behavior per safety requirements, including functional failure conditions and faults and appropriate mitigation in the design.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] These system safety principles underpinning functional safety were developed in the military, nuclear and aerospace industries, and then taken up by rail transport, process and control industries developing sector specific standards.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Functional safety standards are applied across all industry sectors dealing with safety critical requirements and are especially applicable anytime software commands, controls or monitors a safety-critical function.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Thousands of products and processes meet the standards based on IEC 61508: from bathroom showers, automotive safety products, sensors, actuators, diving equipment, Process Controllers and their integration to ships, aircraft and major plants.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The US FAA have similar functional safety certification processes, in the form of ARP4761, US RTCA DO-178C for software and DO-254 for complex electronic hardware, which is applied throughout the aerospace industry.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Functional safety and design assurance on civil/commercial transport aircraft is documented in SAE ARP4754A as functional design assurance levels (FDALS).
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The system FDALs drive the depth of engineering safety analysis.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The level of rigor (LOR) or safety tasks performed to ensure acceptable risk are dependent upon the identification of specific functional failure condition and hazard severity relating to the safety-critical functions (SCF).
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] In many cases functional behavior in embedded software is thoroughly analyzed and tested to ensure the system functions as intended under credible fault and failure conditions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Functional safety is becoming the normal focused approach on complex software intensive systems and highly integrated systems with safety consequences.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The traditional software safety tasks and model based functional safety tasks are performed to provide objective safety evidence that the system functionality and safety features perform as intended in normal and off nominal failures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The entry point of functional safety begins early in the process by performing Functional Hazard Analyses (FHA)to identify hazards and risks and to influence the safety design requirements and functional allocation and decomposition to mitigate hazards.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The behavior of the software and SCFs at the system level is a vital part of any functional safety effort.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Analyses and implementation results are documented in functional hazard assessments (FHA) or system safety assessments or safety cases.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Model-based functional safety processes are often used and required on highly integrated and complex software intensive systems to understand all of the many interactions and predicted behavior and to help in the safety verification and certification process.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] At Boeing, a Safety Review Board (SRB) is responsible for deciding only if an issue is or is not a safety issue.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] An SRB brings together multiple company subject-matter experts (SMEs) in many disciplines.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The most knowledgeable SME presents the issue, assisted and guided by the Aviation Safety organization.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] Any vote for "safety" results in a board decision of "safety".
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] In the US, NASA developed an infrastructure for safety critical systems adopted widely by industry, both in North America and elsewhere, with a standard, supported by guidelines.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The NASA standard and guidelines are built on ISO 12207, which is a software practice standard rather than a safety critical standard, hence the extensive nature of the documentation NASA has been obliged to add, compared to using a purpose designed standard such as IEC EN 61508.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] A certification process for systems developed in accord with the NASA guidelines exists.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The automotive industry has developed ISO 26262 "Road Vehicles Functional Safety Standard" based on IEC 61508.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The certification of those systems ensures the compliance with the relevant regulations and helps to protect the public.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The ATEX Directive has also adopted a functional safety standard, it is BS EN 50495:2010 "Safety Devices Required for the Safe Functioning of Equipment with Respect to Explosion Risks" covers safety related devices such as purge controllers and Ex e motor circuit breakers.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] It is applied by notified bodies under the ATEX Directive.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The standard ISO 26262 particularly addresses the automotive development cycle.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] It is a multi-part standard defining requirements and providing guidelines for achieving functional safety in E/E systems installed in series production passenger cars.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] ISO 26262 is considered a best-practice framework for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The compliance process usually takes time as employees need to be trained in order to develop the expected competencies.
[src:safety-integrity-level/functional-safety] The standard ISO 26262 is considered a best practice framework for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] Functional safety features form an integral part of each automotive product development phase, ranging from the specification, to design, implementation, integration, verification, validation, and production release.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] The standard ISO 26262 is an adaptation of the Functional Safety standard IEC 61508 for Automotive Electric/Electronic Systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] ISO 26262 defines functional safety for automotive equipment applicable throughout the lifecycle of all automotive electronic and electrical safety-related systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] The first edition (ISO 26262:2011), published on 11 November 2011, was limited to electrical and/or electronic systems installed in "series production passenger cars" with a maximum gross weight of 3,500 kilograms (7,700 lb).
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] The second edition (ISO 26262:2018), published in December 2018, extended the scope from passenger cars to all road vehicles except mopeds.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] The standard aims to address possible hazards caused by the malfunctioning behaviour of electronic and electrical systems in vehicles.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] Although entitled "Road vehicles – Functional safety" the standard relates to the functional safety of Electrical and Electronic systems as well as that of systems as a whole or of their mechanical subsystems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] ISO 26262 specifies a vocabulary (a Project Glossary) of terms, definitions, and abbreviations for application in all parts of the standard.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] A resulting *malfunction* that has a *hazardous* effect represents a loss of *functional safety*.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] is applied, that implements a function (or part of a function) at the vehicle level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] is the highest identified object in the process and is thereby the starting point for product-specific safety development under this standard.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] (consisting of hardware parts and/or software units), a single hardware part or a single software unit — effectively, anything in a system that can be distinctly identified and manipulated.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] Discrepancy between a computed, observed or measured value or condition, and the true, specified or theoretically correct value or condition.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] caused by malfunctioning behaviour of Electrical/Electronic systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] ISO 26262 provides a standard for functional safety management for automotive applications, defining standards for overall organizational safety management as well as standards for a safety life cycle for the development and production of individual automotive products.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] and an operational situation of the vehicle with potential to lead to an accident if not controlled by timely driver action.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] as well as the validation and confirmation measures required by the standard to ensure accomplishment of that goal.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] and all levels of requirements decomposed from the safety goals down to and including the lowest level of functional and technical safety requirements allocated to hardware and software components.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] A comprehensive set of *hazardous events* are identified for the *item*.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] An *ASIL* is assigned to each *hazardous event*.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] A *safety goal* is determined for each *hazardous event*, inheriting the ASIL of the hazard.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] A vehicle level *functional safety concept* defines a *system architecture* to ensure the *safety goals*.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] *Safety goals* are refined into lower-level *safety requirements*.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] (In general, each safety requirement inherits the ASIL of its parent safety requirement/goal.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] The architectural components are then *developed* and *validated* in accord with the allocated safety (and functional) requirements.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] ISO 26262 defines objectives for integral processes that are supportive to the Safety Life Cycle processes, but are continuously active throughout all phases, and also defines additional considerations that support accomplishment of general process objectives.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] That is, each hazardous event is assessed in terms of severity of possible injuries within the context of the relative amount of time a vehicle is exposed to the possibility of the hazard happening as well as the relative likelihood that a typical driver can act to prevent the injury.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] At the beginning of the safety life cycle, hazard analysis and risk assessment is performed, resulting in assessment of ASIL to all identified hazardous events and safety goals.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] Risk Management recognizes that consideration of the severity of a possible injury is modified by how likely the injury is to happen; that is, for a given hazard, a hazardous event is considered a lower risk if it is less likely to happen.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] (C) (the relative likelihood that the driver can act to prevent the injury).
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] That is, *ASIL D* is the combination of S3, E4, and C3 classifications.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] *QM* refers to the standard's consideration that below *ASIL A*; there is no safety relevance and only standard Quality Management processes are required.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] These Severity, Exposure, and Control definitions are informative, not prescriptive, and effectively leave some room for subjective variation or discretion between various automakers and component suppliers.
[src:safety-integrity-level/iso-26262] In response, the Society for Automotive Safety Engineers (SAE) has issued *J2980 – Considerations for ISO26262 ASIL Hazard Classification* to provide more explicit guidance for assessing Exposure, Severity and Controllability for a given hazard.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:safety-integrity-level/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] In functional safety, **safety integrity level** (**SIL**) is defined as the relative level of risk-reduction provided by a safety instrumented function (SIF), i.e. the measurement of the performance required of the SIF.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] In the functional safety standards based on the IEC 61508 standard, four SILs are defined, with SIL4 being the most dependable and SIL1 the least.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The applicable SIL is determined based on a number of quantitative factors in combination with qualitative factors, such as risk assessments and safety lifecycle management.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Other standards, however, may have different SIL number definitions.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Assignment, or allocation of SIL is an exercise in risk analysis where the risk associated with a specific hazard, which is intended to be protected against by a SIF, is calculated without the beneficial risk reduction effect of the SIF.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] That unmitigated risk is then compared against a tolerable risk target.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The difference between the unmitigated risk and the tolerable risk, if the unmitigated risk is higher than tolerable, must be addressed through risk reduction of provided by the SIF.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] This amount of required risk reduction is correlated with the SIL target.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] In essence, each order of magnitude of risk reduction that is required correlates with an increase in SIL, up to a maximum of SIL4.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Should the risk assessment establish that the required SIL cannot be achieved by a SIL4 SIF, then alternative arrangements must be designed, such as non-instrumented safeguards (e.g, a pressure relief valve).
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] There are several methods used to assign a SIL.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Of the methods presented above, LOPA is by far the most commonly used in large industrial facilities, such as for example chemical process plants.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The assignment may be tested using both pragmatic and controllability approaches, applying industry guidance such as the one published by the UK HSE.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] SIL assignment processes that use the HSE guidance to ratify assignments developed from risk matrices have been certified to meet IEC 61508.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] There are several problems inherent in the use of safety integrity levels.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] According to IEC 61508, the SIL concept must be related to the dangerous failure rate of a system, not just its failure rate or the failure rate of a component part, such as the software.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Definition of the dangerous failure modes by safety analysis is intrinsic to the proper determination of the failure rate.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The International Electrotechnical Commission's (IEC) standard IEC 61508 defines SIL using requirements grouped into two broad categories: *hardware safety integrity* and *systematic safety integrity*.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] A device or system must meet the requirements for *both* categories to achieve a given SIL.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The SIL requirements for hardware safety integrity are based on a probabilistic analysis of the device.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] In order to achieve a given SIL, the device must meet targets for the maximum probability of dangerous failure and a minimum safe failure fraction.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The concept of 'dangerous failure' must be rigorously defined for the system in question, normally in the form of requirement constraints whose integrity is verified throughout system development.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The actual targets required vary depending on the likelihood of a demand, the complexity of the device(s), and types of redundancy used.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Hazards of a control system must be identified then analysed through risk analysis.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Mitigation of these risks continues until their overall contribution to the hazard are considered acceptable.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The tolerable level of these risks is specified as a safety requirement in the form of a target 'probability of a dangerous failure' in a given period of time, stated as a discrete SIL.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Certification schemes, such as the CASS Scheme (Conformity Assessment of Safety-related Systems) are used to establish whether a device meets a particular SIL.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Third parties that can provide certification include Bureau Veritas, CSA Group, TÜV Rheinland, TÜV SÜD and UL among others.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The requirements of these schemes can be met either by establishing a rigorous development process, or by establishing that the device has sufficient operating history to argue that it has been proven in use.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] Electric and electronic devices can be certified for use in functional safety applications according to IEC 61508.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] There are a number of application-specific standards based on or adapted from IEC 61508, such as IEC 61511 for the process industry sector.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] This standard is used in the petrochemical and hazardous chemical industries, among others.
[src:safety-integrity-level/safety-integrity-level] The following standards use SIL as a measure of reliability and/or risk reduction.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] System Safety is the overarching discipline that aims to achieve safety by reducing risks in technical systems to an acceptable level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] According to the widely adopted system safety standard IEC 61508, safety is “freedom from unacceptable risk of harm”.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] As software alone – which can be considered as pure information – cannot cause any harm by itself, the term software safety is sometimes dismissed and replaced by “software system safety” (e.g. the Joint Software Systems Safety Engineering Handbook and MIL-STD-882E use this terminology).
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] This stresses that software can only cause harm in the context of a technical system (see NASA Software Safety Guidebook, chapter 2.1.2), that has some effect on its environment.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] The goal of software safety is to make sure that software does not cause or contribute to any hazards in the system where it is used and that it can be assured and demonstrated that this is the case.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] This is typically achieved by the assignment of a "safety level" to the software and the selection of appropriate processes for the development and assurance of the software.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] One of the first steps when creating safety-related software is to classify software according to its safety-criticality.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Various standards suggest different levels, e.g.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Software Levels A-E in DO-178C, SIL (Safety Integrity Level) 1-4 in IEC 61508, ASIL (Automotive Safety Integrity Level) A-D in ISO 26262.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] The assignment is typically done in the context of an overarching system, where the worst case consequences of software failures are investigated.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] For example, automotive standard ISO 26262 requires the performance of a Hazard and Risk Assessment ("HARA") on vehicle level to derive the ASIL of the software executed on a component.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] It is essential to use an adequate development and assurance process, with appropriate methods and techniques, commensurate with the safety criticality of the software.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Software safety standards recommend and sometimes forbid the use of such methods and techniques, depending on the safety level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Most standards suggest a lifecycle model (e.g.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] EN 50716, SIL (Safety Integrity Level) 1-4 in IEC 61508 suggests – among others – a V-model) and prescribe required activities to be executed during the various phases of the software.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] The focus on the software development and assurance process stems from the fact that software quality (and hence safety) is heavily influenced by the software process, as suggested by IEC 25010.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] It is claimed that the process influences the internal software quality attributes (e.g. code quality) and these in turn influence external software quality attributes (e.g. functionality and reliability).
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] The following activities and topics addressed in the development process contribute to safe software.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Comprehensive documentation of the complete development and assurance process is required by virtually all software safety standards.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Typically, this documentation is reviewed and endorsed by third parties and therefore a prerequisite for the approval of safety-related software.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] The documentation ranges from various planning documents, requirements specifications, software architecture and design documentation, test cases on various abstraction levels, tool qualification reports, review evidence, verification and validation results etc.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Fig C.2 in EN 50716 lists 32 documents that need to be created along the development lifecycle.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Traceability is the practice to establish relationships between different types of requirements and between requirements and design, implementation and testing artefacts.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] According to EN 50716, the objective “is to ensure that all requirements can be shown to have been properly met and that no untraceable material has been introduced”.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Safety standards can have requirements directly affecting the implementation of the software in source code, such as e.g. the selection of an appropriate programming language, the size and complexity of functions, the use of certain programming constructs and the need for coding standards.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Appropriate test coverage needs to be demonstrated, i.e. depending on the safety level more rigorous testing schemes have to be applied.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Software safety standards typically require some activities to be executed with independence, i.e. by a different person, by a person with different reporting lines, or even by an independent organization.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] This ensures that conflicts of interest are avoided and increases the chances that faults (e.g. in the software design) are identified.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] For example, EN 50716 Figure 2 requires the roles “implementer”, “tester” and “verifier” to be held by different people, the role “validator” to be held by a person with different reporting line and the role “assessor” to be held by a person from a different organizational unit.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] DO-178C and DO-278A require several activities (e.g. test coverage verification, assurance activities) to be executed “with independence”, with independence being defined as “separation of responsibilities which ensures the accomplishment of objective evaluation”.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] In system safety engineering, it is common to allocate upper bounds for failure rates of subsystems or components.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] It must then be shown that these subsystems or components do not exceed their allocated failure rates, or otherwise redundancy or other fault tolerance mechanisms must be employed.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] This approach is not practicable for software.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Software failure rates cannot be predicted with any confidence.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Although significant research in the field of software reliability has been conducted (see for example Lyu (1996), current software safety standards do not require any of these methods to be used or even discourage their usage, e.g.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] 73) states: “Many methods for predicting software reliability based on developmental metrics have been published, for example, software structure, defect detection rate, etc.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] This document does not provide guidance for those types of methods, because at the time of writing, currently available methods did not provide results in which confidence can be placed.” ARP 4761 clause 4.1.2 states that software design errors “are not the same as hardware failures.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Software safety and security may have differing interests in some cases.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] On the one hand safety-related software that is not secure can pose a safety risk, on the other hand, some security practices (e.g. frequent and timely patching) contradict established safety practices (rigorous testing and verification before anything is changed in an operational system).
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Software that employs artificial intelligence techniques such as machine learning follows a radically different lifecycle.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] In addition, the behavior is harder to predict than for a traditionally developed system.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Hence, the question whether and how these technologies can be used, is under current investigation.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Currently, standards generally do not endorse their use.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] For example, EN 50716 (Table A.3) states that artificial intelligence and machine learning are not recommended for any safety integrity level.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Agile software development, which typically features many iterations, is sometimes still stigmatized as being too chaotic for safety-related software development.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] This might be partially caused by statements such as "working software over comprehensive documentation", which is found in the manifesto for agile development.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] Although most software safety standards present the software lifecycle in the traditional waterfall-like sequence, some do contain statements that allow for more flexible lifecycles.
[src:safety-integrity-level/software-safety] DO-178C states that "The processes of a software life cycle may be iterative, that is, entered and reentered." EN 50716 contains Annex C that shows how iterative development lifecycles can be used in line with the requirements of the standard.
